    <item>
      <title>Salt and Silence</title>
      <author> TessWreader </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2421969/salt-and-silence/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2421969-salt-and-silence/chapter/2423168/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">1c6c22ceb943c4f44421b83964aa8b4b905ac5d8</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 01 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;What do you do after the world ends? A trans story about two women and their dog exploring the world after everyone is gone. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2421969-salt-and-silence/chapter/2423168/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;One&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;It started on a Monday, which really should have been the first clue. An overcast sky of greys and blues, wind whipping lost, sun muted and air touched by frigidity. At least campus is never too loud in the mornings. I order my coffee, almost black save for a pinch of milk, and make my way over to a spare table. I pass by a tired bundle of students, ducking their heads and muttering intermittently. I sit down.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My shoulders are stiff. I manage to avoid the walled mirror. I must have stressed some joint. My muscles are a little sore. There's a slight creak in my neck.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jeans on, hoodie dropping down onto my lap, shirt a little too tacky, I cup my chin in my hand and press up against the light splatter of stubble. I've been shaving only occasionally. Morning coffee eats away at my budget, but I compensate by skipping breakfast. My stomach had a little bit of a pickle getting itself accustomed to that particular habit.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I need to get a start on my essay. While my degree isn't regarded as particularly strenuous, effort is still required. And I've been ignoring the reading, too. Which is not great, really, but in the resigned tone of students across our sacred isles: you only need to pass first year. Worrying about grades comes later.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It's always later for me. An annoying pattern I know I will be indulging in more. I glance out of the window, eyes following a couple through the early morning fog, and then I watch them disappear.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The two fade like ghosts, hand in hand, still smiling, as if nothing is wrong. I don't quite recall what I was thinking at that moment, but I remember this impression of something like an axe slicing through water. I turn my head and look around.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There is no one here.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are many ways in which people have imagined the world's end. The moon crashing into the earth, the waves summoned for Noah's timely voyage, the uproar of demons from hellish dominions or the sickly turn of disease twisting the human form. But the actual apocalypse was rather quiet, and done in less than a minute.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I sip on my coffee. It's still warm. I press my palms against the paper. Scalding, even. I follow the steam trails rising into the air. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Huh,” I announce, to clarify my own, apparently stubborn, existence. My voice rings uncomfortably in my throat. The coffee is a little too bitter. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I finish it quietly. Someone must have left an appliance on, because a faint whurr grinds to a stop. The silence feels wrong. I get up and slide the paper cup into the bin, say goodbye to the empty register and press past the glass door.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The wind is chattering. A van has crashed into the side of the physics building. I walk over and inspect the scene. An empty passenger seat, a smashed window, crunched metal. The glossy paint shimmers back a muddled reflection. My fingers coil around each other in my hoodie pocket.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I force myself to breathe. I'm calm, I think. After all, the world ending isn't supposed to feel so dull. It's not right for it to be a Monday, of all days.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hello?” I shout, turning in a circle. There is nobody. What is this, “some sort of rapture?” How strange. I'm pretty sure the rapture is supposed to leave clothes behind, at the very least. No earthly possessions in Heaven, or whatever.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I chuckle at the thought of a colony of believers ascending naked into the sky.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I check the time. My phone still works. I have a lecture in an hour. I was planning on studying in the library for a little bit beforehand. I head down the street. The library gate accepts my card, a buzzing green the only motion of the world.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I set up a desk. My hoodie is covered in sweat. Having forgotten to spray deodorant, I know I must stink. The thought feels sharply ambiguous. I move to browse the catalogue. I'm looking for a textbook, and the website yesterday said there should be a spare copy. I find it sandwiched between a misplaced ‘On Liberty’ and a 9/11 political thriller. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The book is dry. I mean, obviously. To be honest, I don't really care what some academician reckons about the structure of a political theory. Poor bloke is probably so far up his arse he confuses his sniffs for real politics. I snort at the thought and shake my head. No one shushes me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Not that anyone had been in the odd sort of state to shush me before. Most people find such behaviour needlessly awkward, and perhaps a little rude. It's best to just get about your day. A philosophy I too am rather fond of. If you keep at it, life builds around you, so really, you don't need to worry so much. The business of life is dealing with all the small happenings as best as you can. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;You can only worry about something so big for so long. It's exhausting.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My phone buzzes at five minutes to eleven. It's the alarm I set yesterday. It's on seventy four percent battery. The generators will stop working soon, and that's where the real problems will begin. I wonder if the animals have gone too. I nick a charger already plugged into the wall. It still works.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Shouldering my bag, I head down and out. My card is accepted again as I leave. It really is a cold day, the wind buffeting against my hoodie. But the lingering fog has lifted. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The department is, unsurprisingly, empty. I hear my footsteps beat against the hard floor. It's so quiet I can count my breathing. I click my fingers and sip from my water bottle. There's no one in the loo.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I step into the lecture hall and sit down, close to the back as usual, and open my laptop. Blue light flashes my face. I sigh, flicking through a few different tabs. I check the news. Nothing new. A glance around makes that absurd detail even stranger. I scratch my head. My hair is growing out. I like it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Excuse me?” a feminine voice echoes across the room. I startle, making eye contact with a woman some thirty yards away. Her long black hair is well-groomed, her makeup done up quite nicely. I'm envious of her outfit, a leather jacket hugging a crop top, long maxi skirt draping her legs. She looks lost, “Uh. Is this the chemistry department?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shake my head, “Ah, no. You're thinking of the building across the street just opposite. Can't miss it really, what with the giant sign.” She furrows her brows. I cough into my hand, “Sorry. Didn't mean to imply anything. Uh, yeah.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Thank you,” she says in a chilled tone. She turns, gives a slight pause, then asks, “Odd question, do you know where everyone is?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shrug, “I dunno. If I had to guess, I'd say they're all gone.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Confusion settles fully on her face. “Gone?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Like the wind.” I nod.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The wind doesn't go away. There's always wind. You just can't feel it most of the time.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hum in thought, “Then they’re all gone like the rain.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She doubles down, “Rain is precipitation. There's always a little precipitation, except like, in the Sahara. I'm sorry, I don't mean to bother you; it's just a little disconcerting.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I smile politely and say it's fine, “I guess we're in a desert then. What's your name?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Evie,” she says, “I really do hope my lecture is still on. I've been doing my course all online until now. I never thought campus would be so quiet. It wasn't like this on open day.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My smile turns apologetic, “Sorry, but if I had to hazard a guess, I'd say we're the last two people on earth.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“That's too bad,” she takes the seat next to me, sinking into the plush green chair, “what's your name?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Alaya.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The look she gives me is knowing. And then my brain starts unpacking her features, bit by bit. The slight bump signifying a stronger brow, the awkward angles to her jaw, how her jacket squeezes onto her shoulders. “It's nice to meet you,” she says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I dip my head, “likewise.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Last two on earth, huh. How do you know?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hesitate, then incline my head, “guess I just do. I mean, things have been winding down for a while, haven't they? Goodbyes have felt a lot more real. Life has generally just been a lot more floaty. We were all already ghosts. Didn't you notice?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She frowns, “No, not at all. I had a date planned for the evening.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I flick between a few tabs. The internet stops working. “I'm sorry to hear that.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's okay. Not like you're to blame.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I guess.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The conversation stalls. I glance around the hall. Yellow light flickers from over ahead. The large whiteboard feels alien, like something built for a different time. It makes me feel small. I close my laptop.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you believe in God?” Evie asks, interrupting the silence.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don’t know.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She hums, “Isn't it too early to be melancholic?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sorry. I think I'm just like this.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well. If you could do anything in the entire world, what would you do?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And because it feels safe, I answer honestly, “Transition, probably. But it's a little late now.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She shakes her head. Her hair sways nicely, “It's never quite too late. Although, I do have to admit, the timing is a little poor.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I snort, “ain't that the truth.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie suddenly stands, seat wobbling back up straight. She lifts a hand in the air and points up at the sky, “Let's go do that, then!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What, transition?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yup,” and she pops the p.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I stare at her, eyes wide and unblinking. The stare lingers just a little too long. I turn back to the oppressive white, “No, thank you. Let's find some ice cream.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her stance softens, “Why?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Because fridges will stop working soon, and that means no cold food. So if there were a time to eat ice cream, it would be now.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You think we're going to be here for that long?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I stand, packing my things back into my bag. “Don't you feel it?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She hesitates, plucking her lip. We leave the hall and walk down to the store. We walk leisurely. It's only when we get to the freezers that she answers with a faint, “I think I do.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The feeling that we're the last two on Earth. The ones left to turn the lights off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What do you want? Ben and Jerries?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She's a step behind me. “That's bad news for my cut.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I frown, kneeling to admire the selection. “Oh. Are you weight cycling?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Trying to,” she shrugs, “not that it's going very well. I can't stay committed.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You look good as is,” I tell her honestly. I can tell she doesn't believe it. “Have a tub, at least. Today is the sort of day that warrants binge eating.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I grab for myself a tub of cookie dough and go to find a spare spoon. She follows, having chosen a raspberry sorbet. I suppose it is technically healthier. Spoons procured, we lean against a spare wall in the store and dig in.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She eats quietly. My heart starts to stammer with the tempo of a sugar rush. I lick the spoon clean, “chemistry, huh?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes, yes. I'll make us both estrogen.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Thank you.” I say with a smile, “What made you want to study it?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She's only halfway through her sorbet. I excuse myself to grab a Pepsi. “I dunno,” she says as I spin the bottle open, “it just felt right, you know? I figured I could do so much with a chemistry degree. And I liked the idea of being some mad science woman, all hunched in her shed and giggling about world destruction. I was a strange kid.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“On the contrary, there hasn't been a child who doesn't think about conquering the world.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She giggles. It's a nice sound, “true. But I got older, and probably wiser, and chemistry was just this thing I was good at, and it's kind of grown from there.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hum in thought, “So if you didn't know you were good at chemistry, do you reckon you would have done something different?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, maybe. I don't know. People are just reactions to their environments. Change the environment, and you change the person. But there's little point speculating on what ifs.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why?” I take a long sip. The bubbles burn my throat. It makes me feel a little more real.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, it doesn't really do much for resolving what is. Chemistry is complex that way, because an ideal reaction in theory is always imperfect in practice. Life is a litany of impurities.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nod and close my eyes. I match my breathing to hers. It's comfortable. “I guess,” I say, and leave it at that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And what about you? What do you study?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Politics,” I say, and pre-empt the next question with, “because it's easy, and I like to read the news.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My dad thought the news was for melodramatic pessimists. Is that why you're so calm?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I open one eye. Her eyes are dark. “Sure. But then why are you calm, too?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She shifts, “I don't know. I feel like I'm going to freak out later.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Then freak out later. Do you know how to drive?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She sets her tub on the floor. It's finished. “No.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Neither.” I say, “Does it matter?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“There are still cars. The roads must be a mess.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Lucky we live so far from civilisation.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She leans further on the wall, “I think it's lucky we found each other. Loneliness makes you go crazy.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hum, “Yeah. I feel like I've lost my mind a while ago.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Is that something to do with your magical sixth sense?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Nah, just a me thing.” I scratch my wrist, careful not to let the fabric ride too high, “Is there something you'd want to do?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There's a break in the conversation as she thinks. The fridge’s low hum comes to a jittering stop. “Learning a language. I've always liked the sound of Italian. Latin would be useful too.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You must be the only person to think that.” I chide. She shrugs her shoulders. The motion is strained, slightly. Guilt ebbs into me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I dunno. It comes up a lot in science. You'd be surprised. And I always thought it would be funny, because Latin words sound so posh, but it's basically caveman talk. Wise monkey, and all.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nod, “Lots of things sound posh when they aren't.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her lips quirk in a smile, “Is that thing Farage?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We laugh, “Huh. Guess he's gone too.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“At least that's a positive.” She sings, “Always look on the bright side of life.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The right side of death,” I say monotone.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do-doo.” She trails off. Silence returns like a boomerang swung out to the wind. Evie bins the tubs, and we get up and out of the store. The sun is still rising. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie leans against the metal railings. I slouch into my hoodie, a few steps back. I want to avoid the sharp gaze of sunlight. She doesn't seem bothered. The clouds have started to fade. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What now?” I ask, feeling cold. Ice cream may not have been the best of ideas. Not that I regret it. My heart is still beating unusually fast. Sweat claws at my back.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I want to explore.” Evie says after a long moment, “We might find other survivors.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I think we both know we won't, and I can tell she knows that I'm sceptical, at the very least. But I roll my shoulders and ignore the latent stiffness, and agree. We start walking down the road.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We examine the chemistry building first. There's no one there. The lecture halls are expansive and cold, the offices solitary and lonely. Evie goes through an assortment of items, muttering to herself quietly. I watch her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's like we're ghosts,” I say as we leave the building and walk down the steps.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What do you mean?” She asks politely. We head to the physics department.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don't know. It's just… like the tree that falls in a forest, and no one hears. Did it make a noise?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, obviously. Noise doesn't need to be heard for it to be noise.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I dunno,” I say, and leave it there. We scour the physics department. There is nobody. The loo is eerily quiet, a tap still spitting water. I turn it off, turn around, and am affronted by my reflection.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I've never found much joy in the way I look. To me, I may as well be some form of blob, forced to squeeze into clothing and growing hairs at annoying spots. My hair is some shade of dirty blonde, eyes soft brown. I crease my neck and suffer a slight jolt of pain, averting my gaze as I wash my hands. I wonder how long we'll have running water for.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Although I am shorter than Evie. That makes me happy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wipe my hands on my hoodie and exit. The woman spots me from across the lobby. She wanders over, eyes scanning the balcony on the first floor.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What are you using that toilet for?” she asks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Huh?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The men's. You're not a man, right?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shift my shoulders around uncomfortably. “The other loo doesn't feel right. Can we not talk about this? Sorry.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She purses her lips but doesn't say anything. Rather, she gestures up with her head, leans in and whispers, “I think there's something up there.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, shit,” I say, blinking. Then I remember to whisper, “Like what?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I dunno. An animal, maybe. Or a ghost. A survivor?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Let's hope for the latter. Where are the stairs again?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She guides me to the edge of the lobby. We head up. I gesture for us both to stop, sliding off my shoes. Realising what I'm doing, she does the same a moment later. I press the whole of my foot down gently on the floor. Barely a creak is made.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie points to a door. It takes on this ominous quality, garishly painted white, gleaming down the light of the reflecting sun. I position myself opposite Evie, who counts down from three on her fingers. She clenches her fists, peels open the door, forcing me to quickly jump to her side, and we enter the dimly lit room.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A dog, lying down on the floor, perks its head up at us. I let a sigh of relief escape my lungs. The dog quirks its head at me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Just an animal,” I say, forgetting to whisper. Evie gives me a look.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Which means it's just humans who disappeared.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Looks like it.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I turn around, blinking out the dust from my eyes, and see Evie shuffle up to the dog. She scratches the mutt's chin. It purrs gently.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Leave it alone,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why?” She moves onto its belly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's not yours.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“He, actually.” She points to the lower end of the dog's body, “if we're being essentialist about it.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I'm being essential about the fact that we aren't keeping it.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She snorts and continues stroking him, “Who said we're keeping him?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I tut and kneel. The dog meets my eyes. He looks distraught. He must be some form of German shepherd. I don't know the breeds very well. My neighbours used to keep a greyhound. “We're staying together, right?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She nods, “Of course. Loneliness is the number one killer. And you're not transphobic.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I snort, “Isn't it, like diabetes or old age?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“People eat a lot more when they're lonely. And you try to find an old person who isn't alone.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's sort of difficult to find any person now.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She pauses, “True.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I gesture with my head, “What's the name?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She checks the collar, “Scott.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Ew.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You don't like animals with human names?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I scratch my arm through my hoodie, “I dunno. It just doesn't sit right, I guess.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You guess a lot.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I smile half heartedly, “I guess.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She returns the smile. The dog, Scott, I suppose, gets up. His tail is wagging. We head out of the building. Scott follows. I check my phone. It's midday. I spot the sun hiding behind a cloud. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What do you reckon happened?” I ask.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I dunno,” she replies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I stare down the end of the street. If I squint, just a little, and ignore the cadence of the silence, I can almost pretend as if nothing has happened. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You know, I've always wanted to travel,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She hums, “That sounds nice. Where would we go?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shrug, “Italy?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Then why not?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's a little far. And, well, traffic.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The roads must be hellish.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well. Why not go by boat?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And to that I had no answer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She nods as though decided. “We're quite inland though. We should start on a stockpile."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Food and water we can pick up on the way,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Canned food lasts for decades, doesn't it? We have a while to go before we need to start farming.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nod, “At least a decade. Plenty of shops should have boilers. We won't be needing much, really.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So it's just medicine then, isn't it?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nod, “You're on HRT?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She returns it, “Three years in. E and prog. I have enough for a couple more months. We'll have to raid a pharmacy for more. I know my doses. You?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I massage my neck. The pressure lets up. “Ah, no,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why not?” she asks, genuinely curious.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It was always too big. And I just was overwhelmed, I guess.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, would you like to start?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I snort, “What, just like that?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She nods, “Yes, just like that. HRT isn't magic, you know. It's just a drug, same as any other.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I can hear the fear in my mother's voice. “But DIY is dangerous,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She shrugs, “You don't have much of a choice, Missy.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I guess,” I say. The conversation tapers off. Evie starts walking down the road. I follow. Scott wags his tail as he walks. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The silence hurts. I try to fill it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You know, I've always liked pastels.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie humours me, “Pastels? Why?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I scratch my side, “The colour is nice.” &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Your hoodie isn't pastel.” She points out. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I have a pastel one at home.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Of course you do.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why's that an of course?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We walk across the road. Evie checks both ends. I don't bother. “Because you're such a boymoder.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We pass by a couple of spread-out houses. “It's not like it's a choice,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It is,” she says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No, it's not. Not everyone has passing privileges.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sure. But you can just be a non-passing trans woman. They do exist.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I snort, “That's a lot easier for you to say.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I mean, yes. Because I transitioned socially before I started to pass. I don't get why you'd just wait. Isn't it awful?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's like… like a waiting room. My time will come. Just not now.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“But you're not on hormones.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I will be, at some point.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Right. And then what?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I wait.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And then what?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I wait.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It seems to me,” Evie begins, “that a waiting room is a flawed way to think about it. Because what are you waiting for? When will you be good enough? You're the only one who can dismiss yourself.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I'll know when I know.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“But that's never.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I know myself. So it won't ever be never. Just a while.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie is quiet for a long moment. We step into the pharmacy. “The world has ended,” she says finally, “and you're still waiting?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She doesn't respond. Evie pushes past the counter and crouches, opening a cupboard. She pulls out a basket of vials and starts sorting them. “Can you find the needles, please?” she asks. I nod and step past her. An unlocked door leads into a dingy backroom. Cardboard boxes stack the shelves. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The door closes behind me. The room is plunged into darkness. I turn on my phone light. I smell dust.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just for a moment, away from Evie's prying eyes, I am alone again. Lingering guilt creeps into me. It must be awful, to only have me left for company. I open a box. It's filled with pills. I don't recognise the drug name. Really, I had no right to pretend to be friendly with her, didn't I? I am, as she so wisely put it, a melodramatic pessimist. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At least I know I'm not enough.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I find a box filled with needles and other such junk shoved on a high shelf. It takes me standing on my toes to wrangle it off the shelves. I head out. Evie is waiting for me on the other side of the register.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hello, Miss Alaya. Actually, what is your surname?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hayes.” I say, frowning, “What is this, roleplay?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She nods, “Two estrogen, please?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hand her the box. She inspects it. “The needle gauges should work. Want to get started on that boob-making juice?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I scratch my arm through my hoodie, “uhm.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And a hormonal pharmacist, too.” We laugh. The tension softens. I peer over and look at the needles. It looks terrifying. But, here after the world's end, I feel safer too. I nod.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Some ten minutes later, Evie is explaining dosages and how to handle needles, and a quick search for hand sanitiser, my blood is filled with chemicals. It's a new thought, one that rubs up against my old patterns of thinking. Because now it feels like a clock has begun to tick. I know, rationally, that hormones take time and what I'm experiencing is a placebo, but I feel lighter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My chest remains dullishly flat, though. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What now?” I ask as she packs the items away. She nicks my bag and stuffs it with a cardboard box. I don't complain. It's our estrogen, after all. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What a lovely thought. It almost doesn't feel like my own. It's hard to acknowledge. We leave the pharmacy. Scott notices us, trotting over at a leisurely pace. His tail is wagging. I scratch his chin. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Dinner, right?” she asks. We start walking back to campus. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What do you fancy?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A steak would be nice.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hum in agreement. Scott brings us a stick. I throw it down the road. He goes running after it. “Hey, what's your surname?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My chosen one is Gerb,” Evie says from a step behind me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I let her catch up. “You can choose your surname?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Of course you can.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Huh.” Is all I can think to say. I eye our long shadows against the tarmac. Her hair flows freely around her shoulders. It's delightfully straight. I throw the stick again for Scott.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you reckon it really is just us?” she asks after a long pause.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I mean, I don't know.” I say, “But I think so.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Then, why?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shrug, “It just is what it is.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie throws the stick this time. We wait for Scott, then head left down a forked road. He follows, “Do you think it's God?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hum, “Whatever happened, it's definitely supernatural.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What? He just pulled the plug on the entire operation?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Probably.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Then why did He leave us behind?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I scratch my wrist, feeling the skin. “I don't know,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But I have a guess.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We reach the store in the twilight hours of autumn. Scott sits outside, lying down on the concrete and intending to wait for us. We end up pinching a couple of meal deals, and sit outside on an empty bench. Evie is fond of cheese and onion. I go for salt and vinegar.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“How long does it take for sugar to go out of date?” Evie asks. She feeds Scott some jerky. “A while, right?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I think so.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I finish my wrap and slide it into the bin. Evie gives me an appreciative nod. “We should be tidy,, she says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I sit back down. “It does feel a little rude. Almost like the earth is a graveyard.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Spooky.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Scary skeletons.” I sing. She looks at me with a confused expression. I blush. “Send shivers down my spine?” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Never heard of it,” she admits.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Really?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Nope,” and pops the ‘p’, “but it is scary. I'm starting to get cold.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“This is why hoodies are the best.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She sways her head. I finish my crisps. “A good jacket beats a hoodie any day of the week.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Maybe on Thursdays, but not on Fridays.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her laugh is half-hearted. I put up a grin. It doesn't feel real. “Where are we sleeping tonight?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Dorms?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Dorms? Hold on, are you a first year?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Uh. Yes?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Huh.” She says, “I'm in my third year.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I did take a gap year.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She bites her lip. “I see. I'm in student housing. I think we should go there instead. Having a whole house to ourselves is a little preferable, isn't it?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We're sleeping together?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I mean, we should, shouldn't we? What if we lose each other? There's no internet. We'll be alone. I don't want to be alone.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“But like, in the same bed?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She blinks at me, “My house has six bedrooms. You can nick one of those.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The blush burns hotter, “Ah, yeah, I suppose. You like stealing things, huh?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And what is that supposed to mean?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, like. You stole the estrogen. And were happy to come with me to steal ice cream. And we've stolen again. With, um, dinner.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She gives me a hard stare, before breaking character with a snort, “I guess. I mean, it's hardly stealing, isn't it? Not like anyone else will ever use any of this stuff. Free game, for leaving us behind.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“True,” I say, chewing on a double decker.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She changes topic, “Is there anything you'd need from your dorm? We can swing by before going off to bed.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My pyjamas, and a spare change of clothes. Oh, and my toothbrush.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Cool,” she says, getting up. We deposit our rubbish in the bin. Scott clambers off the floor. It's a short walk. My key card is accepted. The dorm smells of alcohol. We head up the stairs and enter my room.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sorry about the smell.” I wince. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's fine,” Evie says. I roll out a suitcase from under the bed and fold away a few clothes. Evie admires my book collection.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A lot of fantasy, huh?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I like Tolkien,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fair. I'm more of a sci-fi gal myself. Why fantasy?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It's interesting. I like worldbuilding. Sanderson's stuff is incredible. Tolkien was also a genius. He made an entire conlang and then had to justify it by writing The Lord of the Rings.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sounds like quite the character. Where is the loo?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Just open the door opposite.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I zip up the suitcase. Evie comes out a moment later and hands me my toothbrush. We head back downstairs. Twilight is approaching a sordid end, the tell-tale signs of night glistening in the air. At least the wind is fresh. Evie guides us to her house, some kilometres away.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I like the moon,” I say to fill the silence.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Evie hums, “I do, too.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Street lighting shines overhead. It has a harshness to it. “Shame about all the light pollution.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She kicks at a lampost. “The generators won't last that long, will they?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Dark by five, then. This is how we used to live. Can you imagine?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, then we invented fire some fifty thousand years ago. So not really.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She takes a long moment to speak, turning down a corner, “We should find some lighters.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A campfire could be fun,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Then let's do that.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There's another lapse in the conversation. I break it with, “You seem really eager to do things.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I am,” she admits, and answers the unspoken question, “because I don't want to go crazy.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Boredom doesn't make you go crazy.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, it does. My mum was a housewife. She got institutionalised.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Ah.” Guilt ebbs, “sorry.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Stop apologising. It's not your fault.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, but I came across as a dick.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Eh,” she waves a hand, “everyone does, on occasion.” She plants her hands on her hips and turns towards a house, “we're here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Looks grand,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Gosh, you sound so middle-aged.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I give her a deadpan stare, “you just said gosh.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, but, ironically.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sure.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She sticks her tongue out at me. We both giggle. She slides open the door a moment later. Scott and I follow. The house smells like her. I like it. I leave my shoes on a rack and haul the suitcase upstairs. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She offers the room just adjacent to hers. The bathroom is filled with makeup products. It feels more than a little awkward sleeping in someone else's bed. The room feels alien, decorated with posters of famous singers. I leave the room mostly untouched, save for the bed and leave the suitcase on the floor.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I brush my teeth and say goodnight to Evie, closing the door. My pyjamas are short-sleeved. I turn off the lights, climb into the bed and make sure the sheets cover me. It's a little hot. And the bed smells funny.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I close my eyes and try to dream. I count the beads of sweat flowing down my skin. I open my eyes and try to figure out the contours of the room. I count imaginary sheep jumping over fences. I get to one hundred and fifty-seven.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The door opens. A pale figure dressed only in a nightgown steps into my room. She's been crying. She peels back the sheets and shuffles in next to me. Her nose is blocked. Two long hands reach out to my own. Her fingers entwine with mine.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Everyone's gone,” she says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes,” I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She traces a long nail against my wrist. Against the scar that I drew. She feels the contour of the bump. Why I don't mind bearing the heat.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You tried to go, too,” she says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes,” I swallow. She lets my arm go and moves in closer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I can't sleep. I feel like my mum. I just can't. It's too much. Please hold me. Please please please.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I move closer. My body feels awkward. I hate it. I really, really do. But she doesn't mind. We pull on the other, legs squeezing arms wrapping eyes weeping. And sleep does finally come, in the arms of the last other woman on earth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
