      <title>The Gallai Priestesses of Cybele</title>
      <author> cutiewiththefire </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2410227/the-gallai-priestesses-of-cybele/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2410227-the-gallai-priestesses-of-cybele/chapter/2415659/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">026cef05ec92e7b235b63af105a1b82ca4f4d8ab</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 27 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the year 55 CE, the galla priestess Sophia is sent by her Archgallus in Argolis to serve their goddess Cybele from her temple in Roma. To any gallai priestess this would be the highest of honors, the chance to serve their goddess from her most sacred and powerful temple within the Roman empire. However, for Sophia, this is no reward, but a punishment. A consequence for her role in the state execution of the former Archgallus of Cybele’s Temple in Argolis for corruption and impiety. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Forbidden from leaving the Temple’s grounds in Roma, Sophia finds herself trapped in an unfamiliar environment surrounded on all sides by enemies and strangers. Separated from her former friends and allies with little chance for escape, Sophia knows she needs to make new relationships fast if she is to survive in a cutthroat city like Roma. Yet through all the scheming and plotting within Cybele’s Roman Temple, is it not possible for Sophia to find friendship among her fellow gallai, even love? Or is this, too, a lie intended to get her guard down?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Considering this story in set in Ancient Rome it grapples with some pretty heavy topics including slavery, sexual violence, genocide, torture, murder, abusive relationships, gender dysphoria, nonconsensual surgery, and suicide. Though I will do my best to add additional warnings for chapters that need them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2410227-the-gallai-priestesses-of-cybele/chapter/2415659/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Prologue: Ascendance of a Galla&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;As with my previous story, I'll do my best to provide somewhat of a glossary at the end marked with an asterisk to explain the mix of ancient/modern Greek, Latin, and Italian terms used in the text.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the outskirts of Argolis, far from its respectable stone walls, a crowd of party-goers drank wine and chatted amicably. Their faces lit only by the glow of fireflies and torches held in their intentions, cloaked under masks made of shadow. Behind them stood the city’s temple devoted to Cybele, its red tiled roof and marble pillars, nearly hidden among the rolling hills and tall trees that lined the roads leading into the city.&lt;br /&gt;Amphorae, handled by servants, were poured as clergy, merchants, and patricians drank heavily and with jubilation. Yet none present were more cheerful and eager than the gallai who, dressed in their bright yellow stolas* and turbans, shrieked and cackled with delight. Drunk on victory and wine, the exuberance of the gallai* bordered that of the pack of maenads after they slayed King Pentheus by their own hands and bathed in his blood. It was a celebration intended to mark the arrival of the new Archgallus* to the Temple, a man by the name of Phillippos, but for the gallai this was a celebration to mark Sophia’s victory over the last Archgallus not celebrate a new one. &lt;br /&gt;The only hesitant exception of the gallai was Sophia, who while smiling at the right times and laughing on cue, was too lost in her own thoughts to relish in her sense of triumph. For as proud as she was that her years of scheming and suffering under Marius’s watchful eye had come to fruition, it had not been without sacrifices. Only time would tell if there would be consequences. &lt;br /&gt;“Down with Marius! Down with the tyrants that steal from our great Goddess!” the gallai priestesses cheered to a roar of applause and stomping. &lt;br /&gt;“Glory to Sophia! She who slayed Cybele’s enemy with her sharp words and wit!” rang out another cheer from her friend, Demerra. The gallai rallied around Sophia, jumping and shouting. Sophia grinning, did the same to keep spirits high among her fellow gallai, even if she didn’t feel the exact joy they did.&lt;br /&gt;Noticing several disapproving looks from the Temple’s wealthy patrons, including from several of her political allies, she was quick to chant out another line of cheers. &lt;br /&gt;“Glory, too, to Phillippos ! Who will surely prove to be a worthy successor as Archgallus!”&lt;br /&gt;This predictably drew last enthusiasm as the previous chants, but her fellow gallai were aware enough of their social circumstances to clap and shout for Phillippos as well. The wealthy patrons nodded their heads along and clapped with Sophia’s chant in a way they hadn’t for the two previous ones. This eased the tightness in her chest. &lt;br /&gt;Her victory over Marius was only possible due to her many connections to the region’s wealthy and powerful patrician class, including the governor of Achaea’s firstborn son, Tiberius. So along with keeping morale high with her gallai contemporaries, Sophia made sure to spend an equal amount of time among her wealthy allies. The most trusted among them, being that of Pausanius, whose father once employed Sophia and her mater Irene as his free-born servants. &lt;br /&gt;“Salve. It’s good to see you again, my friend,” Pausanius greeted when Sophia approached. She went to offer him a handshake, but the tall lanky man chuckled and greeted her with a kiss to both cheeks.&lt;br /&gt;“Sophia, you wound me with such brazen attempts at formality. You and your mother are part of the Makris familia. There is no distance between us,” Pausanius pretended to have been shot with an arrow directly to his heart, stumbling back a step with a goofy grin. Despite laughing it off, Sophia still lowered her head in shame. &lt;br /&gt;“My apologies, Pausanius. I did not mean to offend. With so many daggers pointed at me at once, my movements have been restrained as late,” Sophia hastily explained, but Pausanius as was his good-nature waved it away.&lt;br /&gt;“The gods will surely forgive you, my sister. As will pater* once he gets over his stubborn pride and accepts your decision to live as a galla. It's not like he has many years left to hold a grudge, and even he is not so stubborn as to drag one into death with him.”&lt;br /&gt;“I’m grateful to have a brother as optimistic and joyful as you are, Pausanius. Your good-nature has gotten me through some hard times under Marius,” Sophia thanked, making sure to quickly change the subject so as not to depress him.&lt;br /&gt;“How goes your work as a playwright? The last script you sent with the joke about the dog who chases his abnormally large penis had me and the other gallai roaring with laughter,” Sophia asked, giggling. This seemed to have been the wrong move, as her adoptive brother’s face lost its smile, his forehead furrowing like waves in a turbulent seas. &lt;br /&gt;“It could be better. I struggle to write as of late. Pater has left me to handle the majority of his estate as his health declines, taking up much of my waking moments. I have Pollux to help me, but by the gods I do not have a mind for administration. I do not know how you managed all of Pater’s affairs by yourself at just sixteen,” Pausanius shook his head, his small olive green eyes alight with a sense of inadequacy. &lt;br /&gt;“Pater was firm with me in a way he wasn’t with you and his other children. I knew he had certain expectations and I knew what would happen if I failed to meet them,” Sophia replied, trying to smile, but unable to twist her lips into anything but a grimace. &lt;br /&gt;“Time consuming as it is, I still have enough time in the day to get to the crux of writing great art: getting piss-stinking drunk with other artists as women too clever to be our wives feed us grapes.” Pausanius chuckled.&lt;br /&gt;Sophia smiled politely, saying nothing. It was best to let her wealthy male allies talk for most of their conversations. Most of them just wanted to hear themselves talk anyway. Even from the courtesans who were explicitly trained to be as witty and charming as any educated man, often spoke considerably less than their self-absorbed male patrons. &lt;br /&gt;“Still, they pale in comparison to the symposiums Pater used to host. Remember when he had you read different segments of the Aeneid to confuse you? Just shouting ‘Line 116’, ‘Line 490’, ‘Line 69’ like a mad man,” Pausanius reminisced, fondly. &lt;br /&gt;Sophia discreetly dug her nails into the palm of her clenched right hand as she nodded. &lt;br /&gt;“And you managed to do so, even when it looked like you were about to piss yourself in fear. Pater was always so impressed when you could do that. He said that any other Thracian could never, much less the child of a liberti*. Had you agreed to his offer, he would have sponsored you in any profession that you chose for yourself, but you made your choice as a man and he will eventually have to accept that,” Pausanius said with a well-meaning air, his eyes twinkling down at Sophia. &lt;br /&gt;Despite his attempts at kindness, there were many times Pausanius spoke ignorantly of their childhoods spent together and hurt her. It was done without a hint of malice, but it wounded her all the same as the discus thrown by Apollo when it struck his lover Hycinthus dead. &lt;br /&gt;“I’m sure he will one day, but in the meantime there are more allies I have to consort with before the night is over,” Sophia said, exiting in as polite and calm a way as she could manage. Pausanius nodded, his face calm and serene.&lt;br /&gt;“Of course, go on ahead. I’ll be pestering the servant girls for more wine until then,” he winked. After departing from Pausanius, Sophia drifted from patron to patron with fake smiles and shrill laughter, that quietly tore at her heart. It was necessary work, but with her adoptive brother’s words it brought her memories that stung at her like furious wasps. &lt;br /&gt;As a young child, it was made clear to Sophia that her only role in this life was to make her mater’s employer, Xevros, happy. For Xevros had freed his mater* from a lifetime of slavery, then continued to employ and house both Irene and her pater-less child. So anything less than total obedience to his will would be treated as the most virulent of insults upon his name. This meant that for much of her twenty-five years of life, Sophia was not allowed anything outside of Xevros and the Makris familia. Not hopes, not dreams, not even any passing interests outside of what would please him. The simple life of furniture, doing all it could to be useful to its human owners, so it would not be broken and discarded. A reality, that Pausanius and his siblings could never understand the cruelty of nor would they likely want to if they wanted to keep their pleasant lives intact. Sophia wandered about the party in this light daze, trapped in her script as the eternally grateful servant when through her depressed haze she spotted a surprise guest.&lt;br /&gt;“Glauke? Is that you?” Sophia cried out, her foul mood lifting. The old galla priestess raised her head at the uttering of her name, smiling genuinely with her toothy grin as Sophia embraced her former mentor. &lt;br /&gt;“Sorry we are late, my child. We would have came earlier, but it takes great effort to move these old bones up through the mountains. Thankfully, Leto here was willing to escort me,” Glauke explained, nodding her head to the young galla priestess beside her.&lt;br /&gt;“Its an honor to finally meet you, Sophia. Mater has told me much of what you’ve accomplished since you’ve joined us as a fellow gallai,” Leto said with a demure smile. &lt;br /&gt;“Hope this old woman isn’t filling your head with nonsense, Leto. I’ve only done what was asked of me by our great goddess,” Sophia insisted to the old woman’s cackling laughter. The young galla looking from Sophia to Glauke with wide eyed confusion, only drew more giggling from Glauke who shook her head. &lt;br /&gt;“She’s just being modest, girl. This galla took on a corrupt Archgallus and won. Improving both the temple and the gallai’s living quarters so that neither our goddess or girls like you would have to live in squalor. It’s a great achievement for gallai such as us,” Glauke enthused, her gray eyes sparkling with enthusiasm as Leto listened, enraptured. &lt;br /&gt;“As delighted as I am to have you here, yiayia*, I must ask what has brought you here from Athens? Is the initiation of a new Archgallus as leader of our Temple here in Argolis truly that important to make this trek in your old age?” &lt;br /&gt;“Hey, I still got a few good days in me before I drop over dead,” Gluake answered with a grin, poking Sophia hard in the ribs with a pointed nail. Sophia giggled as Leto, perhaps reflexively, squeezed her mentor’s shoulder in reassurance. &lt;br /&gt;“For whatever the fates may decide, I was told that there would be an important announcement for you tonight, my child.”&lt;br /&gt;“For me?” Now was the time, for Sophia to stare wide-eyed, scanning Gluake’s face and those of the wealthy attendees for any sign of trickery or threat. &lt;br /&gt;“Oh, don’t look so fearful. You’re being honored, Sophia,” Gluake promised. &lt;br /&gt;“With what, yiayia? Am I to be transferred to Cybele’s Temple in Athens as you were?” Sophia asked, trying to quiet the excitement betrayed by her words. &lt;br /&gt;“Maybe,” Gluake teased in a sing-song voice, “but I won’t give up the surprise. You’ll have to hear it from the Archgallus himself.”&lt;br /&gt;“Why? What have you heard, Glauke?” Sophia asked, squinting. It wasn’t that she distrusted the old woman, but she did suspect that she assumed the best of people even when she shouldn’t. A mistake Sophia had, had to learn the hard way many times. &lt;br /&gt;“Only that the future Archgallus himself recommended that you be rewarded with your efforts in Cybele’s name.” Sophia looked warily to the future Archgallus in question. The grey-haired Phillippos Papadakis stood with his back to the gallai, speaking only with a handful of servants and trusted friends.&lt;br /&gt;From what she knew of the man, Phillippos was a first cousin of Marius, having been conscripted into the role as future Archgallus by nature of their shared blood. Before then, Phillippos had lived the comfortable life as a patrician in the countryside outside the Macedonian city of Amphipolis. Meaning his appointment to the out of the way Argolian Temple devoted to Cybele at the age of fifty-eight brought with it a certain resentment that could easily boil to the surface if she didn’t handle the situation with the urgency and grace it required. &lt;br /&gt;“Maybe, I should speak with the soon-to-be Archgallus directly about this reward,” Sophia frowned.&lt;br /&gt;“Oh, don’t do anything rash, my child. The poor man’s lost enough as it is,” Glauke urged, going to squeeze her hand. Sophia easily avoided the old woman’s grip and strode over to where Phillippos stood. She tapped the frail man aristocrat on the shoulder. &lt;br /&gt;“Salve, I hope I am not intruding on a private conversation,” Sophia greeted with a welcoming smile. Phillippos hesitantly turned to her, his tight lips sewn into a distrustful scowl as he regarded her.&lt;br /&gt;“Salve, galla. I was in the middle of speaking with my companions, but I suppose a brief introduction will do,” Phillippos acquiesced offering her his hand. Sophia took it firmly, returning the aristocrat’s tight grip with her own. His fingers were lined with many elegantly crafted gold and bronze rings that dug into her palm, but she refused to be swept off as just another weak and frail galla. &lt;br /&gt;“I am Phillippos Papadakis of Amphipolis, former Lieutenant auxiliary of the nineteenth and later twenty-second legion,” he introduced, drawing faint mummers from the people around them including Glauke and Leto who had been not-so-discreetly listening in. Despite being dressed in fine red and white silk robes, his body covered in more ostentatious jewelry than she could count, that Phillippos still held himself in the way of a trained soldier. His back and shoulders rigid, his feet firmly planted on the ground. &lt;br /&gt;“So, you served during the Battle of Teutoburg Forrest,” Sophia wasn’t afraid to say aloud, gathering more curious stares and whispers to them. Everyone knew of the Varus disaster that had decimated the Roman military and taken three whole legions with it, including the nineteenth. The idea that such a sweeping defeat was made of the Romans by an uncivilized Germanic army had average Romans assuming in both the sheer brutality of the German tribes and the likely cowardice and ineffectual nature of the imperial troops who survived. Any other theories such as the decisiveness of the Germanic forces or the open possibility of more crushing failures made by Roman troops was internally suppressed by a public prone to both panic and an innate sense of ethnic superiority. &lt;br /&gt;“Yes, proudly. I survived the Germanic hordes when many of my contemporaries perished. Then served again to protect Mogantacitum* against those same barbarians, before I was to retire to my familia’s villa. At least, until one of my kin was executed for corruption and I was forced to take his role. Now, who might you be?” &lt;br /&gt;Phillippos was staring intently at her, his face’s sharp angular features reminding Sophia of a hawk as it swept down to catch a field mouse in its clutches. Sophia smirked, undeterred. &lt;br /&gt;“Sophia Markis of Magna Mater’s* Temple in Argolis, at your service,” she spoke, flashing Phillippos a wolfish smile.&lt;br /&gt;“I wanted to personally introduce myself on behalf of my fellow gallai, welcoming you to our humble temple. It is a true honor that a man of such high rank would accept the mantle of Archgallus, here. We trust that you will do our Goddess proud by serving Her humbly and honestly.”&lt;br /&gt;“I likewise trust that you, Sophia Markis, and all your fellow gallai will adhere to the guidelines set forth befitting your status in Her grace’s temple,” Phillippos continued his voice polite, but threaded with threatening venom. &lt;br /&gt;“Of course. We gallai live to serve the Goddess and we respect the role the Archgallus has above us. So long as you treat the Magna Mater and her gallai supplicants with the grace and dignity we deserve. Otherwise, the gods may not catch you if you fall from grace,” Sophia countered with a calm and collected threat of her own. It mattered not who this Archgallus was, no one was going to mistreat her or her fellow gallai without getting their throats torn out in retribution. &lt;br /&gt;“Right. Of course. I aim to serve the Goddess as selflessly, as you have done, Sophia. May your actions prove to be an example to your fellow gallai,” Phillippos replied with a slight pause. &lt;br /&gt;“Speaking of, I was curious to hear what you intend to reward me with and your reasoning for doing so. For I remind you ever so pleasantly, Macedonian, that my allies will respond in kind to any open threats against me,” Sophia asked, plainly. No longer content to keep dancing around the issue. &lt;br /&gt;It felt to her a rarity, but Sophia always thought it was better for people to voice their intentions openly and honestly to avoid any confusion. Phillippos chuckled at her assertion, making the flames in her head grow hot.&lt;br /&gt;“I wouldn’t dare think of it, treasured galla. One who has taken such lengths to honor our Goddess should be justly rewarded, not punished,” Phillippos replied, humbly, his proud head bowed. The gesture silenced the flames in an instant, throwing Sophia into a sea of cold confusion which threatened to drown her. Her thoughts swimming without clear answers, she allowed the Archgallus to take her silently by the shoulders and stride her to the center of the clearing.&lt;br /&gt;“Attention, everyone,” Phillippos announced in a loud, stirring voice. All eyes of the partygoers turned to them; gallai, patron, and servant alike. Sophia’s breath hitched, her heart thundering wildly in her chest.&lt;br /&gt;“I understand that there have been tensions as of late due to my relation to the previous Archgallus Marius. While I admit, I was not pleased to learn of my cousin’s death or of having to uproot myself and my familia to the Greek countryside, I hold no ill will to any who are present here tonight. &lt;br /&gt;“For the truth of the matter is, the fault of his death lay with Marius alone. For it was Marius who stole from the Temple, and it was Marius who forced his gallai subjects to live in a stable as he lived as a king. It is a deeply shameful matter as his blood relation, and I apologize on behalf of him and the Papadakis familia.”&lt;br /&gt;This drew hushed whispers from the crowd with some deeply disgruntled faces among the patrons, including a single wealthy woman who spat with disgust upon the ground and stormed off with her retinue of servants. &lt;br /&gt;“She spat so close to sacred ground,” the crowd whispered in one form or another. Several of the gallai glared at the woman as she passed with a hatred sharp enough to slice glass. It was likely at least one curse tablet was going to be engraved with her name in a few nights’ time. &lt;br /&gt;“It is thus my answer that as I am welcomed as the Archgallus of this Temple that I may reward the main proponent to my cousin’s punishment: Sophia Madakis.”&lt;br /&gt;The patrons and servants politely clapped, as the gallai shrieked and roared with elation. Glauke, grinning proudly up at her, as Demerra and the other gallai spun in circles and poured fresh wine on the earth to honor her. Sophia’s cheeks burned with embarrassment as she struggled to make sense of what was happening. It would likely be considered a public outrage that the relative of a deceased man would condemn Marius, much less in celebration of the woman whose testimony at his impiety and corruption trial saw him executed. By Phillippos doing so, was not only a social taboo among the living such as Marius’s sister Veronica who left in disgust, but also an insult among the deceased members of their entire familia. Deceased relatives who were known to wreak vengeance among those who disrespected them in life, bringing all sorts of plague and misfortune upon them. Why then, would Phillippos do such a thing? &lt;br /&gt;“For in honor of her many achievements, Sophia is to be promoted to serving the Magna Mater from her Temple in Roma!” &lt;br /&gt;If the gallai had been ecstatic before, this move drew the gallai into a divine fervor, swarming up from the trees to pull Sophia into a huddle. Shrieking loudly, as they banged tambourines and shook jingling bells into the air. Sophia, unable to contain herself, joined in their screams of excitement, crying tears of joy. &lt;br /&gt;“Eternal glory to the Magna Mater! Eternal glory to Sophia Madakis!” the gallai women cheered, their voices raised in song. For a brief moment, all Sophia's previous worries and stresses were wiped away with the rising tide drawing her into the tumult of excitement. Thinking and grieving could come later, when the sun had risen and there was no more wine to drink. On that night, they would run through the Greek hills shouting at the moon, waking up the spirits as they passed so all would know of their joy. In their revelry, neither Sophia, nor the other gallai, noticed the cold eyes of Phillippos as he watched them, full of a blazing fire that would scorch the mountains and hills if they ever escaped his skull.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For now, he would wait and he would watch, but in time Phillippos would strike with the fury of a phalanx driving a host of spears into the insolent Sophia's chest, and when that day came, she would be nothing but a cornered wolf; helpless without her pack; and it was that day Philippos was willing to wait as long as it took to take out his prey. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="text-decoration:underline"&gt;Glossary&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Galla/Gallus/Gallai (singular feminine/ singular masculine' plural): The label given to the priestesses of Cybele who after undergoing ritualistic castration would take on a woman's name, wear women's clothing, and live out their lives as women. Though this term is used by both classical Romans and many modern historians to denote a 'male' identity, albeit one that was a eunuch. I reject such framing, as plenty of historical evidence suggests that the gallai themselves considered themselves as a type of woman, likely a cultural gender with many trans-feminine nuances similar to that of the hijra of India and Pakistan and the femminelle of Sicily. Though with no direct writing/quotes from the gallai, all of this is up to interpretation.   &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Stola: The Greco-Roman women's equivalent to a man's toga. Often wore in a way to cover both breasts, while the toga tends to only cover one. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Archgallus: By the time Cybele's worship was adopted by the Roman empire, a new head of Cybele's clergy was firmly established with this title. Unlike his gallai underlings, an Archgallus was expected to hold onto his male identity and not undergo castration. As such he would act as leader of the Temple and over the gallai, often controlling the Temple's administration and finance. Like most male Roman priests, an Archgallus was expected to marry, own property, and have children. For unlike the gallai, who often had varying limits placed on their autonomy like where they could live or be publicly allowed around, an Archgallus had no restrictions placed upon him. Though as leadership positions in Greek and Roman Temples could be involuntary through bloodlines, one might not have always had the choice to become an Archgallus or not. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Liberti: A Latin word meaning freed slave. As was common in the Roman empire, a slave freed by their master would be legally adopted into his familia as would their descendants. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pater: Ancient Greek word for father. Its usage continued for many centuries past the Roman period, but became a term known for its formality. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mater: Ancient Greek word for mother. Its usage continued for many centuries past the Roman period, but became a term known for its formality. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Yiayia: Modern Greek word for grandmother. As you can guess, I tend to play fast and loose between modern and ancient Greek uses of terms.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Magna Mater: Latin for Great Mother was often a second name for Cybele, highlighting her role as both a general mother goddess and her mythological connections to the founding of Roma. As the Roman epic the Aeneid goes, it was Cybele who aided the Trojans in their flight from Troy, where after the Trojans sailed for modern-day Italy and then founded the city of Roma. As such, much of the Roman respect for the goddess, though noticeably not of her gallai priestesshood, were rooted in this mythological story. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mogantacitum: Founded as a Roman fort city along the Rhine River by the general Drusus around 12-13 BCE. In the modern era it is known as the city of Mainz in Germany.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
