      <title>Whatever it Takes</title>
      <author> riversidewings </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2413251/whatever-it-takes/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2413251-whatever-it-takes/chapter/2413256/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">48b4d7bdcaf87ad20c326a1fe7fbdc84ca8092ba</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;After being wounded by otherworldly monstrosities brought forth from hate and empire, Nikki is dying.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her wife Ayako has a plan to save her, but it will come at a price.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They will both need to take a leap of faith.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2413251-whatever-it-takes/chapter/2413256/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;One&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;"Give it to me straight, Doc. I can handle it."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Dr. Robbins' words came gently, but with a gravity well that seemed to suck Houri Nicole Eginian's heart in inexorably. Robbins been her doctor since the move to Seattle, and had been a pleasure to work with. Ordinarily, they even joked back and forth during checkups. But this? This was heavy&lt;i&gt;.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt;Nikki heard the words, she knew what they meant, but it still didn't quite feel real: &lt;i&gt;The kogarasu who took your arm five years ago. Those wounds are temporally u&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;n&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;moored-- in effect, they're still eating you. &lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;I’m afraid t&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;he effect is cumulative. I &lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;am so &lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;sorry.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt;And then Ayako cut in, and brought the erstwhile soldier’s attention back to the here and now.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"She's still being &lt;i&gt;eaten&lt;/i&gt;?!"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Robbins nodded slowly, sadly. "I can pass along the latest science on the subject, Dr. Isawa, but I'm afraid there's nothing we can do. Your wife's got a prognosis of six months at best, given the reports we got from the specialist you saw in Renton. I recommend helping her be as comfortable as possible."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She could hear her heart pounding in her ears. The smell of blood on red clay. The sound of a Stryker’s ammunition cooking off. The rustle of massive corvid wings.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Thrasher&lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt; Six Actual to any station on this net, please respond…&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The scent of grass and maple bark. The eyes of the Chickasaw recon scout going wide.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Yuppa pisa! Okcha!&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm. I'm fine," she mouthed, breathless. "I'm fine."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; "I want to see that research-- I...I have friends," Isawa Ayako stammered, "in the field, they might—"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They needed to stop talking, stop spiraling, they needed to just &lt;i&gt;stop.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm FINE!" Nikki barked. "I...I'm fine."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was a lie, and she knew it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And that was all. They exchanged muted pleasantries. Dr. Robbins wrote her a prescription for opiates-- the good kind, where the pain would be in another galaxy. Then they said their goodbyes. Only outside, in the open air under the tall firs, did her composure fall completely. Beside their car, in the thin mist under an overcast sky, finally safe in Ayako's arms, Nikki wept.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The crows of Fort Sill would receive their due after all.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;The traffic was minimal, and the two of them drove home to Ravenna in silence.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That night, after dinner, Nikki sat alone on the sofa, draped awkwardly over an arm rest out of habit from the recent spike of pain. The meds were doing their job, and the pain was distant and dim, but this much at least was comfortable. Familiar. Schumann's Symphony Number 4 was on the living room speakers, and the house still smelled faintly of the canneles Ayako had baked before dinner.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;At least I get to die somewhere comfortable, &lt;/i&gt;she thought grimly. &lt;i&gt;Keeling over in Lawton, Oklahoma in 104 degree weather would’ve sucked worse.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Leaning against the sofa's other corner, Ayako read through the documents that Dr. Robbins' office had forwarded. Her brow was furrowed and her toes clenched. She’d barely said a word ever since dinner, and while it was understandable, the silence was starting to grow deafening.&lt;br /&gt;Carefully as she could, Nikki shifted in her place, legs curling in to brush at her wife's shins.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Naa, omaesan," she said, voice quiet with all that was unspoken. "Mou iin ja nai ka?" ‹Hey, darling. Why not give it a rest for now?›&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Hm?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"That's...isn't that enough for one day?" She turned to sit with her back against the armrest, facing her wife. It was strange to be able to do that so easily after everything, and she wasn't entirely sure how long it would last.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;But one thing, I know, &lt;/i&gt;she thought to herself, as their eyes met. &lt;i&gt;I want what time I have left to be beside you.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm not letting them have you," Ayako declared.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Babe, c'mon, the doctors are fine, I trust them, they know their shit—"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No, darling.” Ayako's glare was steely-eyed. "I'm &lt;i&gt;talking&lt;/i&gt; about the &lt;i&gt;crows&lt;/i&gt;."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;Fort Sill was once the crown jewel of the Army's artillery branch, the Fires Center of Excellence where artillerists honed their craft and tested new equipment. But it was also the base of the Seventh Cavalry during the Wounded Knee Massacre, and in the Second World War, it was a concentration camp holding Japanese-Americans. It lay heavy with bad history, which had ensured it was consumed by the faewilds soon after the Veil fell two decades earlier.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Going there was bad news, but the Pentagon-- actually, its contractor St. George Arms-- wanted the Dragonslayer artillery shell and relevant data recovered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So the troopers of Charlie Troop, 2/8 Cavalry, rode into the dark that night, five years ago.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What Nikki remembered best about the ride through the barrier and into the faewilds just north of it on I-44 was how everything grew so strangely still. For awhile, it gave her a curious sense of hope: maybe she could bring her company through the mission safely. Buttoned up in the commander's seat of her Stryker, Bushmaster cannon at her fingertips, she told herself she could handle this.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Thrasher Six Actual to all elements. Approaching TRP Sierra. Weapons check."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Two-one. Green."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Thrasher Four-one, Green on weapons."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Three-two! Green!"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Twelve vehicles, 3 platoons-- all 150 people in the company, going over the berm and off the highway, into the treeline.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;I can do this. I can do this....&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And then Nikki was back in the here and now: in Seattle, in the warm embrace of opiates, stripped down to her sports bra and leggings, curled up against a pile of pillows in bed. She was holding a book-- Baronian's &lt;i&gt;Honorable Beggars&lt;/i&gt;-- but she couldn't remember reading.&lt;br /&gt;Clad in her tank top and lounge pants, hair loosely braided, Ayako was standing in the doorway.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Darling."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Wh...yeah?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Where were you just now?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nikki set down the book and rubbed at her tired eyes. "On I-44 busting over the berm into Sill."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I thought so," she sighed. "You looked a thousand miles away."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Thereabouts." Fingers reflexively tangled around the cord of her magatama necklace, Nikki tried to still her breath and remember where and when she was. The texture of the polished basalt was reassuring against her palm. "Fuck, what a day."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Leaning lazily against the doorframe, Ayako folded her arms. "I had an idea in the shower, and I wanted to run it by you."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Mm?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It's about Reed resonators."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Reed resonators? &lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;The fuck? &lt;/i&gt;&lt;i&gt;What does the new-model doll chassis have to do with being eaten in slow motion for five years?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Ayako's company, and her life's work, was in cybernetics and bridging the magical and technological. It was natural that she would see a solution there, but Nikki wasn't sure if it made any sense at the moment.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nikki turned, shaped her fingers into the proper kuji, and with effort between limbs both biological and technological, managed to light the stick of cedarwood in its little holder atop the crowded bedside table.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Maybe I'll have them light cedarwood incense at my funeral.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Where is this going, love?" she sighed. "I'm bushed. I don’t have it in me to do shop talk."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Ayako huffed, climbed into the bed, and gently draped an arm over her wife's waist.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I've had a theory about how to improve Ashlynne and Shiloh's chassis design-- something that'd get rejection rates down to nearly zero." Her hand lingered over the curve of Nikki's belly, rubbing in slow, deliberate circles. "It'd be a leap of faith, but you'd be free of the pain and still keep up your practice in the Daoist arts."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The &lt;i&gt;and still here with me&lt;/i&gt; was unspoken, but plain-- almost strong enough to obscure Nikki’s misgivings over the entire idea of re-sleeving into a doll chassis.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;How am I going to hold you with a body made of wood and steel? &lt;/i&gt;Nikki silently asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ayako, dearest,” she heard herself plead, voice barely above a whisper. “Let's talk about it in the morning."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nikki felt her wife freeze, as if something was on the tip of her tongue.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"We don't have forever,” Ayako murmured. “And I don’t want to lose any time.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I know. But right now, it can wait." The smoke of incense, as if harried by unseen wind, traced a thin line beside her. "Right now, I'm tired and scared, and...and I just want my wife to hold me."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Here, in her wife's arms where she belonged, it was safe. The last of her tension fell away, and she felt tired, tired down to her bones. With her eyes on the thin trail of incense, and the warmth of Ayako pressing close behind her, Nikki finally let sleep claim her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Everything else could wait until tomorrow.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
