      <title>Can&amp;#8217;t See Straight</title>
      <author> catboymettaton </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2394968/cant-see-straight/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2394968-cant-see-straight/chapter/2408049/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">29cba4eb67fdaef1ba4e335a292a78acc6dc56c4</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;An awkward, myopic guy breaks his glasses. Fortunately, his best friend's girlfriend knows a place that can help! Maybe it'll solve some other problems, too...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2394968-cant-see-straight/chapter/2408049/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Prologue: Roll for Initiative&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;My alarm sounded far too early for a Saturday. Ugh, it was still well before noon. Why would I need to be awake when I didn’t have class?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I fumbled for my phone, squinting at the screen. Oh, right. I had D&amp;amp;D today. Why had I agreed to meet so early? Oh well, there was nothing to do about it now. I put on my glasses and dragged myself out of bed and into the kitchen. I poured myself a bowl of Cheerios and a glass of milk. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;As I caught up with my morning Discord messages, a reminder popped up at the top of my phone. I was supposed to schedule an eye appointment soon. On the rare occasions I went outside, I’d noticed the distance getting blurry. But my prescription was just fine for staring at my computer, and all my lectures were posted online, which gave me yet another reason not to leave my apartment. Anyway, I’d rather put off shopping for new glasses as long as I could. Buying new frames was always torturous. Every time, I thought that maybe they’d have come up with a design that made my face look less hideous, but I never had any luck. Plus, they never seemed to make frames that could fit a nose with virtually no bridge, except for nose pads that felt even worse. So I just stuck with the reliable thick black squares, hoping maybe they’d block out the worst of my features. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I finished my Cheerios and dumped the dishes in the sink, which I promptly decided not to consider any further. I wasn’t having anyone over anytime soon, so the only person who had to deal with the mess was me, and I was getting really good at ignoring it. Sooner or later, Aisha would somehow appear at my door and insist on taking care of it, and I'd feel bad for letting a woman do my dishes, but I wouldn't stop her because surely that would be worse, somehow.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Just then, my phone buzzed with a text from Aisha, as if she knew I’d been thinking of her.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;Aisha: &lt;/b&gt;goooooood morning, sleepyhead! ready for the session? &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;me: &lt;/b&gt;morning. just had breakfast &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;Aisha:&lt;/b&gt; yayyy great job!!! &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;Aisha:&lt;/b&gt; do you wanna come to ikea with me and vicky after the session?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I missed Aisha. It had been a while since we hung out last. But going to IKEA and hanging out with Victoria, too, sounded intimidating. IKEA was full of people, who would see me and notice that I was a total loser. Especially next to Victoria. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Victoria was such a good fit for Aisha. They were both funny, and confident, and also breathtakingly gorgeous. But I'd known Aisha for years, and talking to her was easy. Victoria, on the other hand, still intimidated me. We liked a lot of the same shows, which meant that if I was wrong about them, she'd know. Just looking at her made my heart start racing. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;me:&lt;/b&gt; sorry. gotta work on a paper&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;This was true. I did have papers to write. But I was probably going to leave them till tomorrow anyway, and squander the rest of my Saturday losing to 12 year olds at chess or rewatching Gundam or lying in bed staring vacantly at the ceiling. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;Aisha:&lt;/b&gt; booooo papers&lt;b&gt;👎&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;Aisha: &lt;/b&gt;but seriously that's okay, maybe you can come next time?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;b&gt;me:&lt;/b&gt; yeah maybe&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;We both knew I wouldn’t, though.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I sat down at my computer and opened up the tabs I needed. Discord server, virtual tabletop, online player’s handbook, because even though I looked like the kind of loser who had the the whole thing memorized I always ended up freezing under pressure. I pulled my earbuds out of my drawer, which had, of course, become hopelessly tangled up with each other. I really needed to order a new pair of wireless headphones, but this was even less urgent than doing the dishes, so I kicked it down my to-do list.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Aisha and Victoria’s profile pictures appeared in the voice chat, so I joined in. It didn’t take long for the others to join, as well. This was the only party I’d ever played with who actually showed up on time to most sessions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;We set off into the town, trying to gather information for our quest. The cleric suggested we split up, and thankfully Aisha and Victoria agreed I should go with their characters. I still barely knew the rest of the party. They were all Aisha’s friends, not mine, and I had trouble keeping track of their character names and their actual names. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;It was a roleplay heavy session, which was always my least favorite part. I liked the idea of games like D&amp;amp;D where you could become someone else for a little while, someone more confident and intelligent who knew how to talk to other people. My character was a charismatic bard, nothing at all like my clumsy self who couldn’t even carry a tune. It was nice to be able to roll dice and do cool things.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;But roleplaying meant I had to make myself charismatic, too, and I had no idea how to do that. Everyone else slipped effortlessly into their character voices, perfectly embodying the traits on their sheets. They knew how to become clerics and druids and barbarians, even when their real personalities were entirely different. Even out of character, they knew how to joke with each other around the virtual table, hyping each other up and groaning and their terrible puns.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Unlike me. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I appreciated that Aisha had invited me. She'd gotten so busy, and it was hard to hang out often. But I couldn’t help feeling like I didn’t really belong at the table. Not next to all these gorgeous, confident women. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Aisha had suggested I try playing as a woman, too, but something about that felt wrong. Sure, I could pretend to be a musical genius who knew how to talk to girls, but actually &lt;i&gt;being&lt;/i&gt; a girl felt like a bridge too far. It felt like some sort of appropriation. Something I shouldn’t be allowed to have. So my character was the sole dude in a party of women, just like me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Maybe that was why the rest of the party understood each other. All my life I’d heard whispers of some secret “girl code” that every girl seemed to understand. Maybe girls had a secret language that carried with them into womanhood. Maybe that was the reason I didn’t understand them. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;span&gt;We’re a troupe of traveling performers,” Aisha’s character was saying. “Here, let us demonstrate our talents!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;We rolled the appropriate dice. I landed a solid 18, so my song was an excellent success. I heard cheering from the other party members. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;span&gt;Come on, sing for us!” &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I gulped. Maybe I shouldn’t have made my bard a singer. I could’ve made him a drummer and then all I would’ve had to do was smack my desk a little. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;span&gt;Uh… I am a super awesome bard and I love to sing my songs and everybody likes my songs!” I improvised, then cringed at the sound of my own voice. Surely I could do better than that. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“&lt;span&gt;Very nice, thank you.” She had to be humoring me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Why had I agreed to be a bard? I should’ve been the barbarian or rogue or some other physical class. Sure, I wasn’t strong or agile in real life, either, but no one expected a barbarian to be able to recite slam poetry on the fly.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Finally, the session drew to a close. I stared at the empty voice channel, replaying my conversations. Did I say anything wrong? What could I have done better?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I opened up chess.com and tried to take my mind off of things. I wasn’t any better at chess than I was at roleplaying, but at least it didn’t involve talking. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;After a few games, I noticed my glasses were smudged. I sighed, took them off, and polished them with the edge of my shirt. I knew I was supposed to use one of those nice microfiber cloths, but mine all had a habit of disappearing, swallowed up by the black hole of my room. Oh well, the shirt handled the job well enough. I scrubbed off the left lens as best as I could, then moved to the right, and then all of a sudden there was a horrible cracking sound.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Oh no.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
